Massachusetts elected five Federalists, one Anti-Federalist, and two
representatives unaffiliated with either party to the First Congress.
The elections within the Congressional districts were in several
instances contested within the Federalist party rather than against the
Anti-Federalists. In the fourth Congressional district, Theodore
Sedgwick defeated Samuel Lyman by only 17 votes out of 4,387 votes cast.
